1. Overview\n\nThis notebook goes through exploratory data analysis (EDA) and modeling for the [Playground Series - Season 6 Episode 7 - Predicting Student Health Risk competition](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/playground-series-s6e7/overview).\n\nThe goal of the competition is to predict each student's health risk (`health_condition`) — a multi-class classification task with three levels: `fit`, `at-risk`, and `unhealthy` — based on their lifestyle, physiological, and psychological attributes.\n\nThe dataset (both train and test) was inspired by the College Student Health Behavior Dataset and synthesised.\n\nNote: Feature distributions are close to, but not exactly the same as, the original (source: [Dataset Description](https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/playground-series-s6e7/data))","metadata":{"_kg_hide-input":false}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# §2. Data\n\nThe competition dataset (train and test) was synthesized from a deep learning model inspired by and trained on the [College Student Health Behavior Dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ziya07/college-student-health-behavior-dataset), so feature distributions are close to, but not identical to, the original. That original dataset is described as a comprehensive student health dataset of 50,000 records, built to capture the wide-ranging lifestyle, physiological, and psychological characteristics of college students. It is modeled on trends from large-scale student health studies conducted in China, giving realistic variation in daily habits and health-related attributes, and it integrates information from surveys, wearable devices, and institutional health records — spanning lifestyle behaviors, psychological indicators, and time-series data.\n\nColumn descriptions:\n\n* `id` — identifier;\n* `sleep_duration` — hours of sleep per observation;\n* `heart_rate` — measured heart rate (bpm);\n* `bmi` — body mass index;\n* `calorie_expenditure` — calories burned;\n* `step_count` — number of steps taken;\n* `exercise_duration` — time spent exercising;\n* `water_intake` — daily water consumption;\n* `diet_type` — category of diet (`veg`, `non-veg`, `balanced`) followed;\n* `stress_level` — reported level of stress (`low`, `medium`, `high`);\n* `sleep_quality` — self-reported quality of sleep (`poor`, `average`, `good`);\n* `physical_activity_level` — overall level of physical activity (`sedentary`, `moderate`, `active`);\n* `smoking_alcohol` — smoking and alcohol habit category (`no`, `occasional`, `yes`);\n* `gender` — gender (`male`, `female`, `other`);\n* `health_condition` — target variable; student health class (`fit`, `at-risk`, `unhealthy`);\n\nSource: [College Student Health Behavior Dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ziya07/college-student-health-behavior-dataset)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"data_dir = \"/kaggle/input/competitions/playground-series-s6e7\"\ntrain_path = os.path.join(data_dir, \"train.csv\")\ntrain = pd.read_csv(train_path)\n\ntest_path = os.path.join(data_dir, \"test.csv\")\ntest = pd.read_csv(test_path)\n\nsample_submission_path = os.path.join(data_dir, \"sample_submission.csv\")\nsample_submission = pd.read_csv(sample_submission_path)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"train","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"general_stats = train.describe(include=\"all\").transpose()\ngeneral_stats","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"From the description and a first look at the data, we can group the columns by their nature:\n\n* Identifier: `id`\n* Numerical features: `sleep_duration`, `heart_rate`, `bmi`, `calorie_expenditure`, `step_count`, `exercise_duration`, `water_intake`\n* Ordinal features: `stress_level`, `sleep_quality`, `physical_activity_level`\n* Categorical features: `diet_type`, `smoking_alcohol`, `gender`\n* Target: `health_condition`\n\nBased on this classification we can set up appropriate preprocessing for each group (e.g. scaling for numerical features, order-aware encoding for ordinal features, and categorical encoding (One-Hot, Target encoding, etc.) for categorical features).","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"id_column = \"id\"\nnumerical_features = [\n    \"sleep_duration\", \"heart_rate\", \"bmi\", \"calorie_expenditure\", \n    \"step_count\", \"exercise_duration\", \"water_intake\",\n]\nordinal_features = [\"stress_level\", \"sleep_quality\", \"physical_activity_level\"]\ncategorical_features = [\"diet_type\", \"smoking_alcohol\", \"gender\"]\ntarget_column = \"health_condition\"","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.1 Target `health_condition`\n\nThe dataset includes a target variable, `health_condition`, which classifies students into three categories:\n\n* `fit` – representing balanced and healthy conditions\n* `at-risk` – indicating moderate health concerns\n* `unhealthy` – representing higher levels of health risk\n\nSource: [College Student Health Behavior Dataset](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ziya07/college-student-health-behavior-dataset)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"figure = plt.figure()\nax = figure.add_subplot()\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=\"health_condition\", \n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=ax, \n    yticks=range(0, 600_000, 75_000),\n)\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Class imbalance. The target is dominated by `at-risk` (85.9%), while `fit` (5.8%) and unhealthy `(8.4%)` are small minorities — a roughly 15:1 majority-to-minority ratio. Stratified splitting and cross-validation with probability calibration are essential so the minority classes aren't washed out. ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.2 `gender`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"gender\"\nfeature_palette = gender_palette\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(11, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    palette=feature_palette,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\nfeature_vs_target_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    order=list(feature_palette.keys()),\n    hue_order=list(health_condition_palette.keys()),\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=feature_vs_target_ax,\n    annotate=False,\n    legend=\"health_condition\",\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Roughly balanced gender split. `male` (34.5%), `female` (32.5%), and `other` (30.0%) are fairly even, with only a mild skew toward male — no gender dominates the data.\n* Health-condition mix is consistent across genders. Each gender shows the same pattern — at-risk overwhelmingly dominant, with small, similar fit and unhealthy counts — so the target imbalance holds within every gender group rather than being driven by one.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.3 `sleep_duration`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"sleep_duration\"\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\ntarget_vs_feature_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    hue_order=[\"fit\", \"unhealthy\", \"at-risk\"],\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=target_vs_feature_ax,\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Overall sleep is centered on a healthy ~7 hours. The pooled distribution is roughly bell-shaped with $\\mu$ = 6.99, $\\sigma$ = 1.22, spanning about 3–10 hours — a plausible, well-behaved feature with no extreme skew.\n* `sleep_duration` separates the classes clearly — the standout among features so far. `unhealthy` students sleep least ($\\mu$ = 5.37), `at-risk` sit in the middle ($\\mu$ = 7.09), and `fit` sleep most ($\\mu$ = 7.95), a clean monotonic ordering that matches the ordinal target (`unhealthy` → `at-risk` → `fit`).","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.4 `heart_rate`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"heart_rate\"\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\ntarget_vs_feature_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    hue_order=[\"fit\", \"unhealthy\", \"at-risk\"],\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=target_vs_feature_ax,\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Heart rate is a clean, symmetric bell centered on ~75 bpm ($\\mu$ = 75.10, $\\sigma$ = 8.18), spanning roughly 50–100 — a normal, physiologically plausible range with no skew or outlier tails, so it's a well-behaved feature needing no transformation.\n\n* The three classes overlap almost entirely. All health conditions peak around the same ~75 bpm with near-identical spread, so unlike `sleep_duration`, `heart_rate` shows little standalone separating power — it likely contributes mainly through interactions with other features rather than on its own.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.5 `bmi`\n\nBody mass index (BMI) is a value derived from the mass (weight) and height of a person. BMI is calculated as the body mass, in kilograms ($\\text{kg}$), divided by the square of the body height, in square metres ($\\text{m}^2$); although the quotient has units of kilograms per square metre, BMI is most often reported normalized by 1 $\\text{kg}/\\text{m}^2$, thus as a pure number.\n\n$$\n\\text{BMI} = \\frac{\\text{mass}_{\\text{kg}}}{\\text{height}_{\\text{m}}^2}\n$$\n\nSource: [Body mass index](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_mass_index)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"bmi\"\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\ntarget_vs_feature_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    hue_order=[\"fit\", \"unhealthy\", \"at-risk\"],\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=target_vs_feature_ax,\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* BMI is a tight, symmetric bell centered at $\\mu = 22.98$ ($\\sigma = 2.48$), sitting squarely in the healthy range (~18.5–25) and spanning roughly 15–32 with only a slight right tail — a clean feature with no problematic skew.\n\n* The classes overlap heavily, but there's a subtle signal: `unhealthy` extends a bit further into the higher-BMI tail (past ~27) than `fit`, while `fit` leans slightly lower, so BMI carries mild separating power at the extremes even though the bulk of all three classes coincides around 23.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.6 `calorie_expenditure`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"calorie_expenditure\"\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\ntarget_vs_feature_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    hue_order=[\"fit\", \"unhealthy\", \"at-risk\"],\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=target_vs_feature_ax,\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Calorie expenditure is bimodal — a small secondary peak near ~1800 and a dominant one around ~2200 — so the single summary ($\\mu = 2226.08$, $\\sigma = 347.53$) hides real structure; the two humps likely reflect distinct activity subpopulations and may warrant a derived binary/binned feature.\n\n* The class split follows the overall shape closely, with `at-risk` tracing both humps, so calorie expenditure alone separates the classes only weakly — though the smaller ~1800 mode could carry some signal worth probing in interaction with activity-related features.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.7 `step_count`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"step_count\"\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\ntarget_vs_feature_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    hue_order=[\"fit\", \"unhealthy\", \"at-risk\"],\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=target_vs_feature_ax,\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Step count is broad and roughly uniform (with a gentle rise toward higher counts) rather than bell-shaped, spanning ~500–15,500 with $\\mu = 8615.95$ and a large $\\sigma = 3929.40$ — the wide, flat spread means it splits students across a full activity range rather than clustering.\n\n* This is one of the more separating features: `unhealthy` concentrates at the low end (few steps), `fit` shifts distinctly toward the high end (its density peaks past ~12,500), and `at-risk` fills the middle — a clear activity gradient that matches the ordinal target and complements the `sleep_duration` signal.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.8 `exercise_duration`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"exercise_duration\"\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\ntarget_vs_feature_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    hue_order=[\"fit\", \"unhealthy\", \"at-risk\"],\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=target_vs_feature_ax,\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Exercise duration is a broad bell centered near ~40 min ($\\mu = 38.75$, $\\sigma = 14.74$) with a distinct spike at exactly 0 — a separate \"does not exercise\" subpopulation the smooth summary misses; a binary `exercises_at_all` flag would capture this cleanly.\n\n* The classes separate along duration: `unhealthy` leans toward the low/zero end, `fit` shifts toward the higher durations (~40–70 min), and `at-risk` dominates the middle — a monotonic activity gradient consistent with `step_count` and the ordinal target, making this a useful feature.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.9 `water_intake`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"water_intake\"\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(13, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\ntarget_vs_feature_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_numeric_dist(\n    data_frame=train,\n    col=feature,\n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    hue_order=[\"fit\", \"unhealthy\", \"at-risk\"],\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=target_vs_feature_ax,\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Water intake is a fairly symmetric bell centered at ~2.2 L ($\\mu = 2.19$, $\\sigma = 0.52$), spanning roughly 0.5–4 L with a slight bump near ~3 L — a well-behaved feature with no problematic skew.\n\n* The three classes overlap almost completely, all peaking together at ~2.2 L, so water intake carries little standalone separating power for `health_condition` and likely matters only in combination with other features.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.10 `stress_level`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"stress_level\"\nfeature_palette = stress_level_palette\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(11, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    palette=feature_palette,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\nfeature_vs_target_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    order=list(feature_palette.keys()),\n    hue_order=list(health_condition_palette.keys()),\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=feature_vs_target_ax,\n    annotate=False,\n    legend=\"health_condition\",\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Stress level is fairly balanced, skewed toward `medium` (37.9%), with `low` (24.3%) and `high` (25.8%) close behind — a well-populated ordinal feature with no rare category.\n\n* Stress is strongly and cleanly separating — arguably the best categorical predictor so far. `fit` appears almost only at `low` stress, `unhealthy` almost only at `high`, and `medium` is essentially pure `at-risk`. Each class occupies a distinct stress band with little cross-over, mapping tightly onto the ordinal target (`low`→`fit`, `medium`→`at-risk`, `high`→`unhealthy`).\n\n* This near-deterministic structure suggests stress level alone carries a large share of the signal — worth confirming it isn't a near-leaky proxy for the target, and it should interact well with the physiological features (sleep, activity).","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.11 `sleep_quality`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"sleep_quality\"\nfeature_palette = sleep_quality_palette\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(11, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    palette=feature_palette,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\nfeature_vs_target_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    order=list(feature_palette.keys()),\n    hue_order=list(health_condition_palette.keys()),\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=feature_vs_target_ax,\n    annotate=False,\n    legend=\"health_condition\",\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Sleep quality is almost perfectly balanced across `poor` (30.7%), `average` (31.0%), and `good` (29.8%) — a uniform ordinal feature with no rare category.\n\n* It separates the minority classes in the expected direction, but weakly. `at-risk` dominates every category (mirroring the overall imbalance), while within the minorities the gradient is clear: `unhealthy` is highest at `poor` and shrinks toward `good`, and `fit` does the opposite — rising from `poor` to `good`.\n\n* The signal is directional but soft — every sleep-quality level is still overwhelmingly `at-risk`, so unlike `stress_level`, sleep quality nudges the minority probabilities rather than cleanly splitting the classes. Useful in combination, not decisive alone.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.12 `physical_activity_level`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"physical_activity_level\"\nfeature_palette = physical_activity_level_palette\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(11, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    palette=feature_palette,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\nfeature_vs_target_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    order=list(feature_palette.keys()),\n    hue_order=list(health_condition_palette.keys()),\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=feature_vs_target_ax,\n    annotate=False,\n    legend=\"health_condition\",\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Sleep quality is almost perfectly balanced across `poor` (30.7%), `average` (31.0%), and `good` (29.8%) — a uniform ordinal feature with no rare category.\n\n* It separates the minority classes in the expected direction, but weakly. `at-risk` dominates every category (mirroring the overall imbalance), while within the minorities the gradient is clear: `unhealthy` is highest at `poor` and shrinks toward `good`, and `fit` does the opposite — rising from `poor` to `good`.\n\n* The signal is directional but soft — every sleep-quality level is still overwhelmingly `at-risk`, so unlike `stress_level`, sleep quality nudges the minority probabilities rather than cleanly splitting the classes. Useful in combination, not decisive alone.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.13 `diet_type`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"diet_type\"\nfeature_palette = diet_type_palette\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(11, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    palette=feature_palette,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\nfeature_vs_target_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    order=list(feature_palette.keys()),\n    hue_order=list(health_condition_palette.keys()),\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=feature_vs_target_ax,\n    annotate=False,\n    legend=\"health_condition\",\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Diet type is evenly split across `non-veg` (32.6%), `balanced` (32.9%), and `veg` (33.5%) — a balanced categorical feature with no rare level.\n\n* It carries essentially no separating power: the `fit`/`at-risk`/`unhealthy` proportions are nearly identical across all three diet types, each dominated by `at-risk` in the same ratio. Diet type looks non-predictive on its own and may only contribute marginally through interactions.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.14 `smoking_alcohol`","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"feature = \"smoking_alcohol\"\nfeature_palette = smoking_alcohol_palette\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(11, 5))\n\nax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    palette=feature_palette,\n    ax=ax,\n)\n\nfeature_vs_target_ax = figure.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=train, \n    col=feature, \n    hue=\"health_condition\",\n    order=list(feature_palette.keys()),\n    hue_order=list(health_condition_palette.keys()),\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=feature_vs_target_ax,\n    annotate=False,\n    legend=\"health_condition\",\n)\n\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Smoking/alcohol is evenly distributed across `no` (31.8%), `occasional` (31.6%), and `yes` (32.4%) — a balanced ordinal feature with no rare level.\n\n* It moves the minority classes in the expected direction, though modestly. Going from `no` → `occasional` → `yes`, `fit` steadily declines while `unhealthy` steadily rises; `at-risk` stays dominant and roughly flat throughout.\n\n* The gradient is real but soft — every level is still overwhelmingly `at-risk`, so like `sleep_quality` this feature nudges the `fit`/`unhealthy` odds rather than cleanly separating classes. Useful in combination, not decisive alone.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.15 Correlation","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"figure = numeric_pair_grid(\n    train, \n    numerical_features, \n    hue_order=list(health_condition_palette.keys()),\n    sample=4000,\n)\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Numerical features are almost entirely uncorrelated with each other — most pairwise Pearson coefficients sit at $r \\approx 0.00$. The only exceptions form one small activity cluster: `calorie_expenditure`–`step_count` ($r = 0.40$), `calorie_expenditure`–`exercise_duration` ($r = 0.39$), and `step_count`–`exercise_duration` ($r = 0.44$) — all mild, all sensibly linking the movement-related measures. Everything else (sleep, heart rate, BMI, water intake) is effectively independent.\n\n* Despite the near-zero linear correlations, the scatter panels show clear class structure that $r$ can't capture. Horizontal bands appear along `sleep_duration` — `unhealthy` points concentrate in a low-sleep stripe (~5–6 h) and `fit` in a high-sleep stripe — confirming sleep separates classes even though it doesn't correlate with other features. Vertical gaps/bands appear along `calorie_expenditure` (the bimodal ~1800 vs ~2200 split) and near `exercise_duration = 0` (the \"no exercise\" spike), reflecting the sub-populations seen in the 1-D plots.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.16 Missing values (per column and per sample)","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"missing_values_count = (train.isnull().sum(axis=0) / train.shape[0]) * 100\nmissing_values_count = missing_values_count.sort_values(ascending=False)\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))\nax = figure.add_subplot()\n\nsns.barplot(\n    x=missing_values_count.index,\n    y=missing_values_count.values,\n    color=\"#E24B4A\",\n    legend=False,\n    edgecolor=\"black\",\n    ax=ax,\n    saturation=1,\n)\n\nax.set_ylabel(\"Percentage\")\nax.set_xlabel(\"\")\nax.set_title(\"Missing values per column\")\nax.tick_params(axis=\"x\", rotation=90)\n\nstyle_axis(ax)\nfigure.tight_layout()\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Missingness is present in nearly every feature but modest — the highest are `stress_level` (~12%) and `sleep_duration` (~11%), tapering down through the rest to ~1%, while `id` and the target `health_condition` have none (as they must).\n\n* There's a striking pattern: the columns with the most missingness are exactly the strongest predictors. `stress_level`, `sleep_duration`, and `sleep_quality` — the features that separated the classes best — top the list, while weak/non-predictive features like `diet_type` and `exercise_duration` are the most complete. This suggests missingness may not be fully random, so how we handle it matters.\n\n* No column is missing enough to drop. Imputation is straightforward (median for numeric, mode/\"missing\" category for categorical/ordinal), but because the informative columns are the ones with gaps, it's worth adding explicit \"was-missing\" indicator flags — the fact that a value is absent could itself carry signal. Tree models like LightGBM/XGBoost also handle NaNs natively, which is another reason they suit this dataset.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"na = train.isna()\nna = na[na.mean().sort_values(ascending=False).index]\n\nfigure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))\nax = figure.add_subplot()\n\nsns.heatmap(\n    na,\n    cbar=False,\n    cmap=[\"#EAEAEA\", \"#E24B4A\"],\n    yticklabels=False,\n    ax=ax,\n)\nax.set_title(\"Missing values\")\nax.tick_params(axis=\"x\", rotation=90)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n\n* Missingness looks scattered rather than block-structured — the red marks are spread fairly evenly down each column with no wide horizontal stripes cutting across many columns at once, so there's little sign that whole rows go missing together. Missing values appear largely independent across columns.\n\n* The per-column density matches the bar chart: `stress_level` and `sleep_duration` are visibly the densest (occasional thick clusters of adjacent rows), the middle columns thin out, and `id`/`health_condition` are clean. The few short thick bands within a single column (e.g. runs in `stress_level`, `calorie_expenditure`) hint at small localized clusters, possibly tied to ordering, but they don't span columns.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §2.17 Duplicates","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"columns = set(train.columns) - {\"id\", \"health_condition\"}\nduplicates = train[train.duplicated(subset=columns)]\nduplicates","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Insights**\n* There are no duplicates in training dataset.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# §3. Modeling","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.1 Metric\n\nSubmissions are scored using **balanced accuracy**, which compares the predicted class against the true target. Unlike plain accuracy, it weights every class equally regardless of size, making it well suited to this heavily imbalanced problem where `at-risk` dominates.\n\nIt is defined as the average of the per-class recall scores:\n\n$$\n\\text{Balanced Accuracy} = \\frac{1}{n} \\sum_{i=1}^{n} \\text{Recall}(C_i),\n\\qquad\n\\text{Recall}(C_i) = \\frac{TP_i}{TP_i + FN_i}\n$$\n\nwhere $n$ is the number of classes and $\\text{Recall}(C_i)$ is the recall for class $C_i$ — the fraction of that class's true members the model correctly identifies. Averaging recall across all classes means a model cannot score well simply by predicting the majority class; it must recognize the minority `fit` and `unhealthy` classes too.\n\nThis is available directly in scikit-learn as [`balanced_accuracy_score`](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.metrics.balanced_accuracy_score.html).","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.metrics import balanced_accuracy_score","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.2 Cross-validation\n\n\nBecause the `health_condition` target is imbalanced, a stratified splitting strategy is preferable. scikit-learn provides this through [StratifiedKFold](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.StratifiedKFold.html), which keeps each class's proportion consistent across every fold. The right validation strategy is crucial, especially in Kaggle competitions.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold\n\nnum_folds = 5\nshuffle = True\nrandom_seed = 13\n\ncv_strategy = StratifiedKFold(\n    n_splits=num_folds, \n    shuffle=shuffle, \n    random_state=random_seed,\n)\nfolds = list(cv_strategy.split(\n    X=train, y=train[target_column].values, groups=None,\n))","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"compute_target_dist = lambda data, target_column: (data[target_column].value_counts() / data.shape[0]) * 100\ngeneral_target_dist = compute_target_dist(train, target_column)\ndists = [general_target_dist]\nfor fold, (train_indices, val_indices) in enumerate(folds, 1):\n    fold_train_target_dist = compute_target_dist(train.iloc[train_indices], target_column)\n    fold_val_target_dist = compute_target_dist(train.iloc[val_indices], target_column)\n    dists.extend([fold_train_target_dist, fold_val_target_dist])\ndists = pd.DataFrame(\n    dists,\n    index=(\n        [\"general\"] +\n        [x\n        for k in range(1, num_folds + 1)\n        for x in (f\"fold_{k}_train\", f\"fold_{k}_val\")\n        ]\n    ),\n)\n\nclass_order = [\"fit\", \"at-risk\", \"unhealthy\"]\ntrain_max = 100 - 100 / num_folds\nval_max = 100 / num_folds\n\nfig = plt.figure(figsize=(14, 1.1 * (num_folds + 1) + 1))\ngs = fig.add_gridspec(num_folds + 1, 2, width_ratios=[train_max, val_max])\n\nax_general = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, :])\naxes = [[fig.add_subplot(gs[r, 0]), fig.add_subplot(gs[r, 1])] for r in range(1, num_folds + 1)]\n\ndef draw_bar(ax, row_name, total):\n    left = 0.0\n    for cls in class_order:\n        pct = dists.loc[row_name, cls]\n        w = pct / 100 * total\n        ax.barh(0, w, left=left, height=0.6,\n                color=health_condition_palette[cls], edgecolor=\"black\")\n        ax.text(left + w / 2, 0, f\"{pct:.2f}%\",\n                    va=\"center\", ha=\"center\", fontsize=8)\n        left += w\n    ax.set_xlim(0, total)\n    ax.set_ylim(-0.5, 0.5)\n    ax.set_yticks([])\n    ax.tick_params(length=0)\n    for sp in (\"top\", \"right\", \"left\"):\n        ax.spines[sp].set_visible(False)\n\ndraw_bar(ax_general, \"general\", 100)\nax_general.set_ylabel(\"general\", rotation=0, ha=\"right\",\n                      va=\"center\", fontweight=\"bold\", labelpad=25)\nax_general.set_title(\"full dataset\", fontsize=13, fontweight=\"bold\", loc=\"left\")\n\nfor i in range(num_folds):\n    draw_bar(axes[i][0], f\"fold_{i + 1}_train\", train_max)\n    draw_bar(axes[i][1], f\"fold_{i + 1}_val\", val_max)\n    axes[i][0].set_ylabel(f\"fold #{i + 1}\", rotation=0, ha=\"right\",\n                          va=\"center\", fontweight=\"bold\", labelpad=25)\n\naxes[0][0].set_title(\"train\", fontsize=13, fontweight=\"bold\", loc=\"left\")\naxes[0][1].set_title(\"val\", fontsize=13, fontweight=\"bold\", loc=\"left\")\naxes[-1][0].set_xlabel(\"Percentage of dataset (%)\")\naxes[-1][1].set_xlabel(\"Percentage of dataset (%)\")\n\nhandles = [Patch(facecolor=health_condition_palette[c], edgecolor=\"black\", label=c)\n           for c in class_order]\nfig.legend(handles=handles, title=\"health_condition\", ncol=3,\n           loc=\"upper center\", bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, 1.02), frameon=False)\n\nfig.tight_layout()\nfig.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"_kg_hide-input":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.3 Feature engineering\n\nInstead of feeding raw columns straight into the models, we engineer features directly from the EDA findings above:\n\n* **Missingness is informative (§2.16)** — the most-missing columns (`stress_level`, `sleep_duration`, `sleep_quality`) are also the strongest predictors, so we keep explicit `*_is_missing` flags rather than silently imputing them away, and leave the underlying NaNs for the boosters to split on natively.\n* **Ordinal features stay ordinal** — `stress_level`, `sleep_quality`, `physical_activity_level`, `smoking_alcohol` are mapped to integers that preserve their natural order (§2.10–§2.12), instead of being one-hot encoded and losing that structure.\n* **Weak-alone, useful-together signals get combined** — `step_count`, `exercise_duration`, and `calorie_expenditure` were each mildly separating on their own (§2.7–§2.8) and mildly correlated with each other (§2.15), so we roll them into a single `activity_score`. The `exercise_duration` spike at 0 (§2.8) and the `calorie_expenditure` bimodality (§2.6) each get their own binary flag.\n* **True categoricals stay categorical** — `diet_type`, `gender`, and a derived `bmi_band` are passed as native `category` dtype so LightGBM/XGBoost/CatBoost can split on them directly instead of via lossy one-hot or noisy target encoding.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def engineer_features(df):\n    df = df.copy()\n\n    # --- Informative-missingness indicators (EDA §2.16) ---\n    miss_cols = [\"stress_level\", \"sleep_duration\", \"sleep_quality\", \"heart_rate\", \"bmi\"]\n    for c in miss_cols:\n        df[f\"{c}_is_missing\"] = df[c].isna().astype(int)\n    df[\"n_missing\"] = df[numerical_features + ordinal_features].isna().sum(axis=1)\n\n    # --- Ordinal encoding, preserving order (EDA §2.10-2.12) ---\n    ordinal_maps = {\n        \"stress_level\": {\"low\": 0, \"medium\": 1, \"high\": 2},\n        \"sleep_quality\": {\"poor\": 0, \"average\": 1, \"good\": 2},\n        \"physical_activity_level\": {\"sedentary\": 0, \"moderate\": 1, \"active\": 2},\n        \"smoking_alcohol\": {\"no\": 0, \"occasional\": 1, \"yes\": 2},\n    }\n    for c, mapping in ordinal_maps.items():\n        df[f\"{c}_ord\"] = df[c].map(mapping)\n\n    # --- Engineered signal features, motivated by the EDA insights ---\n    df[\"exercises_at_all\"] = (df[\"exercise_duration\"] > 0).astype(int)          # §2.8 zero-spike\n    df[\"calorie_high_mode\"] = (df[\"calorie_expenditure\"] > 2000).astype(int)     # §2.6 bimodality\n    df[\"activity_score\"] = (\n        df[\"step_count\"].rank(pct=True)\n        + df[\"exercise_duration\"].rank(pct=True)\n        + df[\"calorie_expenditure\"].rank(pct=True)\n    )\n    df[\"sleep_stress_gap\"] = df[\"sleep_duration\"] - df[\"stress_level_ord\"] * 2   # §2.3 x §2.10 interaction\n    df[\"bmi_band\"] = pd.cut(\n        df[\"bmi\"], bins=[0, 18.5, 25, 30, 100],\n        labels=[\"under\", \"normal\", \"over\", \"obese\"],\n    )\n    df[\"steps_per_exercise_min\"] = df[\"step_count\"] / df[\"exercise_duration\"].replace(0, np.nan)\n\n    return df\n\n\ntrain_fe = engineer_features(train)\ntest_fe = engineer_features(test)\n\nnew_numeric = [\"activity_score\", \"sleep_stress_gap\", \"steps_per_exercise_min\", \"n_missing\"]\nnew_binary = [\"exercises_at_all\", \"calorie_high_mode\"] + [f\"{c}_is_missing\" for c in\n              [\"stress_level\", \"sleep_duration\", \"sleep_quality\", \"heart_rate\", \"bmi\"]]\nnew_ordinal = [f\"{c}_ord\" for c in\n               [\"stress_level\", \"sleep_quality\", \"physical_activity_level\", \"smoking_alcohol\"]]\nmodel_categorical = [\"diet_type\", \"gender\", \"bmi_band\"]\n\nmodel_features = numerical_features + new_numeric + new_binary + new_ordinal + model_categorical\n\nfor c in model_categorical:\n    train_fe[c] = train_fe[c].astype(\"category\")\n    test_fe[c] = test_fe[c].astype(\"category\")\n\nX_all = train_fe[model_features]\nX_test = test_fe[model_features]\ncat_feature_idx = [X_all.columns.get_loc(c) for c in model_categorical]\n\nmodel_features","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.4 Sample weighting for the balanced-accuracy metric\n\nThe competition metric (§3.1) is **balanced accuracy** — the mean of per-class recall — not plain accuracy. If we train with the default (accuracy-oriented) loss, the ~86% `at-risk` majority dominates the gradient and the model under-fits `fit`/`unhealthy`.\n\nRather than bolting on a post-hoc decision threshold, we align the *training* objective with the *evaluation* metric directly: each sample is weighted by the inverse frequency of its class, so every class contributes equally to the loss — the same principle balanced accuracy rewards at evaluation time.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder\n\nlabel_encoder = LabelEncoder()\ny_all = label_encoder.fit_transform(train_fe[target_column])\nclass_order_enc = label_encoder.classes_        # alphabetical order, e.g. [at-risk, fit, unhealthy]\nn_classes = len(class_order_enc)\n\nclass_counts = pd.Series(y_all).value_counts().sort_index().values\nclass_weight_arr = train_fe.shape[0] / (n_classes * class_counts)   # one weight per encoded class\nsample_weight_all = class_weight_arr[y_all]\n\npd.Series(class_weight_arr, index=class_order_enc, name=\"class_weight\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### GPU acceleration\n\nAll three boosters can train on GPU (Kaggle's GPU accelerator gives a large speedup, especially with the 2000-iteration budgets and multi-seed averaging used below). GPU support is probed once per library — with a tiny 1-iteration fit — and each library falls back to CPU independently if its GPU build isn't available, so the notebook still runs correctly on a CPU-only session, just slower.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import lightgbm as lgb\nimport xgboost as xgb\nfrom catboost import CatBoostClassifier\n\nSEEDS = [13, 42, 2026]\n\n\ndef _gpu_probe(name, build_and_fit):\n    try:\n        build_and_fit()\n        return True\n    except Exception as e:\n        # Print the *actual* error, not just its type -- otherwise a genuine GPU\n        # incompatibility and an unrelated bug (e.g. a probe sample missing a class)\n        # look identical and get silently swallowed the same way.\n        print(f\"{name}: GPU unavailable/unsupported -> falling back to CPU.\")\n        print(f\"    reason: {type(e).__name__}: {e}\")\n        return False\n\n\n# Stratified probe sample so every class is guaranteed to be present, even though\n# `fit`/`unhealthy` are rare (§2.1) -- a random 200-row slice risks missing one\n# entirely and raising an unrelated \"single class\" error that has nothing to do\n# with GPU availability.\n_probe_idx = np.concatenate([\n    np.where(y_all == c)[0][:80] for c in range(n_classes)\n])\n_probe_X, _probe_y = X_all.iloc[_probe_idx], y_all[_probe_idx]\n\nUSE_GPU_LGB = _gpu_probe(\"LightGBM\", lambda: lgb.LGBMClassifier(\n    device_type=\"cuda\", n_estimators=1, verbosity=-1,\n).fit(_probe_X, _probe_y))\n\nUSE_GPU_XGB = _gpu_probe(\"XGBoost\", lambda: xgb.XGBClassifier(\n    tree_method=\"hist\", device=\"cuda\", n_estimators=1, enable_categorical=True,\n).fit(_probe_X, _probe_y))\n\nUSE_GPU_CAT = _gpu_probe(\"CatBoost\", lambda: CatBoostClassifier(\n    task_type=\"GPU\", devices=\"0\", iterations=1, verbose=False, cat_features=cat_feature_idx,\n).fit(_probe_X, _probe_y))\n\nprint(f\"LightGBM GPU: {USE_GPU_LGB} | XGBoost GPU: {USE_GPU_XGB} | CatBoost GPU: {USE_GPU_CAT}\")\n","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.5 Hyperparameter tuning (optional)\n\nThe model cells below already ship with reasonably strong, hand-tuned defaults (shallow-ish trees, moderate regularization, low learning rate + early stopping) so the notebook is runnable out of the box. For a further edge, wrap any of the three model-builders in an [Optuna](https://optuna.org/) study that maximizes **OOF balanced accuracy** (not log-loss) — the snippet below shows the pattern for LightGBM; the same structure applies to XGBoost/CatBoost by swapping the model and search space.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Optional: uncomment to run a light Optuna search (kept short — 30 trials — to stay\n# within typical Kaggle session limits). Run this *after* the GPU-probe cell below so\n# USE_GPU_LGB is defined. Feed `best_params` into the LightGBM call in §3.6.\n\n# import optuna\n#\n# def lgb_objective(trial):\n#     params = dict(\n#         n_estimators=2000,\n#         learning_rate=trial.suggest_float(\"learning_rate\", 0.01, 0.05, log=True),\n#         num_leaves=trial.suggest_int(\"num_leaves\", 15, 127),\n#         min_child_samples=trial.suggest_int(\"min_child_samples\", 10, 100),\n#         subsample=trial.suggest_float(\"subsample\", 0.6, 1.0),\n#         colsample_bytree=trial.suggest_float(\"colsample_bytree\", 0.5, 1.0),\n#         reg_alpha=trial.suggest_float(\"reg_alpha\", 1e-3, 5.0, log=True),\n#         reg_lambda=trial.suggest_float(\"reg_lambda\", 1e-3, 5.0, log=True),\n#     )\n#     scores = []\n#     for tr_idx, val_idx in folds[:2]:               # subset of folds for speed\n#         model = lgb.LGBMClassifier(\n#             objective=\"multiclass\", num_class=n_classes, random_state=13, verbosity=-1,\n#         device_type=(\"cuda\" if USE_GPU_LGB else \"cpu\"), **params,\n#         )\n#         model.fit(\n#             X_all.iloc[tr_idx], y_all[tr_idx], sample_weight=sample_weight_all[tr_idx],\n#             eval_set=[(X_all.iloc[val_idx], y_all[val_idx])],\n#             callbacks=[lgb.early_stopping(100, verbose=False)],\n#         )\n#         pred = model.predict(X_all.iloc[val_idx])\n#         scores.append(balanced_accuracy_score(y_all[val_idx], pred))\n#     return np.mean(scores)\n#\n# study = optuna.create_study(direction=\"maximize\")\n# study.optimize(lgb_objective, n_trials=30)\n# best_params = study.best_params","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.6 Diverse gradient-boosting ensemble with multi-seed OOF\n\nA single model, no matter how well tuned, has a single point of view. We instead train **three architecturally different GBMs** — LightGBM, XGBoost, CatBoost — each averaged over **multiple random seeds**, all under the same `StratifiedKFold` split defined in §3.2. This gives:\n\n* Model diversity (different split-finding algorithms and regularization biases) for the ensemble to exploit.\n* Seed diversity, which cheaply reduces variance from a single lucky/unlucky tree sequence.\n* Honest, leakage-free out-of-fold (OOF) predictions for every model — the currency we'll use in §3.7 to *optimize* the ensemble weights instead of guessing them.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def run_cv_model(model_name, X, y, sample_weight, X_test, folds, cat_features=None, seeds=SEEDS,\n                  extra_X=None, extra_y=None, extra_w=None):\n    \"\"\"Train `model_name` with StratifiedKFold x multi-seed averaging, on GPU when available.\n\n    Returns (oof_probs, test_probs). `extra_*`, if given, are always added to each\n    fold's *training* data only (e.g. pseudo-labels) — never to validation, so OOF\n    balanced accuracy stays an honest estimate.\n    \"\"\"\n    n = len(X)\n    oof = np.zeros((n, n_classes))\n    test_preds = np.zeros((len(X_test), n_classes))\n    fold_scores = []\n\n    for seed in seeds:\n        oof_seed = np.zeros((n, n_classes))\n        for tr_idx, val_idx in folds:\n            X_tr, X_val = X.iloc[tr_idx], X.iloc[val_idx]\n            y_tr, y_val = y[tr_idx], y[val_idx]\n            w_tr = sample_weight[tr_idx]\n\n            if extra_X is not None:\n                X_tr = pd.concat([X_tr, extra_X], ignore_index=True)\n                y_tr = np.concatenate([y_tr, extra_y])\n                w_tr = np.concatenate([w_tr, extra_w])\n\n            if model_name == \"lgb\":\n                params = dict(\n                    n_estimators=2000, learning_rate=0.02, num_leaves=63,\n                    min_child_samples=40, subsample=0.8, colsample_bytree=0.7,\n                    reg_alpha=0.5, reg_lambda=0.5, objective=\"multiclass\",\n                    num_class=n_classes, random_state=seed, verbosity=-1,\n                )\n                params[\"device_type\"] = \"cuda\" if USE_GPU_LGB else \"cpu\"\n                model = lgb.LGBMClassifier(**params)\n                model.fit(\n                    X_tr, y_tr, sample_weight=w_tr,\n                    eval_set=[(X_val, y_val)],\n                    callbacks=[lgb.early_stopping(100, verbose=False)],\n                )\n                val_pred = model.predict_proba(X_val)\n                test_pred = model.predict_proba(X_test)\n\n            elif model_name == \"xgb\":\n                params = dict(\n                    n_estimators=2000, learning_rate=0.02, max_depth=7,\n                    min_child_weight=10, subsample=0.8, colsample_bytree=0.7,\n                    reg_alpha=0.5, reg_lambda=0.5, objective=\"multi:softprob\",\n                    num_class=n_classes, tree_method=\"hist\", enable_categorical=True,\n                    random_state=seed, early_stopping_rounds=100, eval_metric=\"mlogloss\",\n                )\n                if USE_GPU_XGB:\n                    params[\"device\"] = \"cuda\"\n                model = xgb.XGBClassifier(**params)\n                model.fit(X_tr, y_tr, sample_weight=w_tr, eval_set=[(X_val, y_val)], verbose=False)\n                val_pred = model.predict_proba(X_val)\n                test_pred = model.predict_proba(X_test)\n\n            elif model_name == \"cat\":\n                params = dict(\n                    iterations=2000, learning_rate=0.03, depth=7, l2_leaf_reg=5,\n                    loss_function=\"MultiClass\", cat_features=cat_features,\n                    random_seed=seed, early_stopping_rounds=100, verbose=False,\n                )\n                if USE_GPU_CAT:\n                    params.update(task_type=\"GPU\", devices=\"0\")\n                model = CatBoostClassifier(**params)\n                model.fit(X_tr, y_tr, sample_weight=w_tr, eval_set=(X_val, y_val))\n                val_pred = model.predict_proba(X_val)\n                test_pred = model.predict_proba(X_test)\n\n            else:\n                raise ValueError(model_name)\n\n            oof_seed[val_idx] = val_pred\n            test_preds += test_pred / (len(folds) * len(seeds))\n            fold_scores.append(balanced_accuracy_score(y_val, np.argmax(val_pred, axis=1)))\n\n        oof += oof_seed / len(seeds)\n\n    print(f\"{model_name}: OOF balanced accuracy = \"\n          f\"{balanced_accuracy_score(y, np.argmax(oof, axis=1)):.5f} \"\n          f\"(fold mean {np.mean(fold_scores):.5f} +/- {np.std(fold_scores):.5f})\")\n    return oof, test_preds\n\n\noof_lgb, test_lgb = run_cv_model(\"lgb\", X_all, y_all, sample_weight_all, X_test, folds)\noof_xgb, test_xgb = run_cv_model(\"xgb\", X_all, y_all, sample_weight_all, X_test, folds)\noof_cat, test_cat = run_cv_model(\"cat\", X_all, y_all, sample_weight_all, X_test, folds,\n                                  cat_features=cat_feature_idx)\n\noof_dict = {\"lgb\": oof_lgb, \"xgb\": oof_xgb, \"cat\": oof_cat}\ntest_dict = {\"lgb\": test_lgb, \"xgb\": test_xgb, \"cat\": test_cat}","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.7 OOF ensemble-weight optimization (hill-climbing)\n\nFixed blend weights picked by eye (like the original `0.6*a + 0.4*b`) are a guess. Since we now have honest OOF probabilities for every model, we can instead **search for the weights that directly maximize OOF balanced accuracy** — the exact competition metric, on data the models never trained on. We use greedy hill-climbing (a coordinate search over the weight simplex) rather than a smooth optimizer like `scipy.optimize.minimize`, because balanced accuracy is piecewise-constant (it comes from an `argmax`), so gradient-based methods have nothing to follow.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def balanced_acc_of_blend(weights, oof_dict, y_true):\n    names = list(oof_dict.keys())\n    blend = sum(w * oof_dict[name] for w, name in zip(weights, names))\n    return balanced_accuracy_score(y_true, np.argmax(blend, axis=1))\n\n\ndef hill_climb_weights(oof_dict, y_true, step=0.05, max_rounds=200):\n    names = list(oof_dict.keys())\n    weights = {name: 1 / len(names) for name in names}\n    best_score = balanced_acc_of_blend(list(weights.values()), oof_dict, y_true)\n\n    for _ in range(max_rounds):\n        improved = False\n        for name in names:\n            for delta in (step, -step):\n                trial = weights.copy()\n                trial[name] = max(0.0, trial[name] + delta)\n                total = sum(trial.values())\n                trial = {k: v / total for k, v in trial.items()}\n                score = balanced_acc_of_blend(list(trial.values()), oof_dict, y_true)\n                if score > best_score + 1e-6:\n                    weights, best_score, improved = trial, score, True\n        if not improved:\n            break\n    return weights, best_score\n\n\nown_weights, own_oof_score = hill_climb_weights(oof_dict, y_all)\nprint(\"Optimized own-model weights:\", {k: round(v, 3) for k, v in own_weights.items()})\nprint(f\"Own-ensemble OOF balanced accuracy: {own_oof_score:.5f}\")\n\nown_blend_oof = sum(w * oof_dict[name] for name, w in own_weights.items())\nown_blend_test = sum(w * test_dict[name] for name, w in own_weights.items())","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.8 Pseudo-labeling\n\nA well-known technique for squeezing extra signal out of a large unlabeled test set: take the test rows our current ensemble is *most confident* about, treat its predicted label as ground truth, and fold them into training as extra (down-weighted) samples. Re-running the same leakage-safe CV — pseudo-rows are added to every fold's training set only, never to validation — lets us check honestly whether this actually improves OOF balanced accuracy before trusting it.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = 0.98\n\nown_test_pred_labels = np.argmax(own_blend_test, axis=1)\nown_test_pred_conf = own_blend_test.max(axis=1)\nconfident_mask = own_test_pred_conf >= CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD\npseudo_idx = np.where(confident_mask)[0]\n\nprint(f\"Pseudo-labeling {len(pseudo_idx)} / {len(test_fe)} confident test rows \"\n      f\"({len(pseudo_idx) / len(test_fe):.1%})\")\n\npseudo_X = X_test.iloc[pseudo_idx].reset_index(drop=True)\npseudo_y = own_test_pred_labels[pseudo_idx]\npseudo_w = class_weight_arr[pseudo_y] * 0.5   # down-weight: these labels are model-derived, not ground truth\n\noof_lgb_pl, test_lgb_pl = run_cv_model(\n    \"lgb\", X_all, y_all, sample_weight_all, X_test, folds,\n    extra_X=pseudo_X, extra_y=pseudo_y, extra_w=pseudo_w,\n)\noof_xgb_pl, test_xgb_pl = run_cv_model(\n    \"xgb\", X_all, y_all, sample_weight_all, X_test, folds,\n    extra_X=pseudo_X, extra_y=pseudo_y, extra_w=pseudo_w,\n)\noof_cat_pl, test_cat_pl = run_cv_model(\n    \"cat\", X_all, y_all, sample_weight_all, X_test, folds, cat_features=cat_feature_idx,\n    extra_X=pseudo_X, extra_y=pseudo_y, extra_w=pseudo_w,\n)\n\noof_dict_pl = {\"lgb\": oof_lgb_pl, \"xgb\": oof_xgb_pl, \"cat\": oof_cat_pl}\ntest_dict_pl = {\"lgb\": test_lgb_pl, \"xgb\": test_xgb_pl, \"cat\": test_cat_pl}\n\npl_weights, pl_oof_score = hill_climb_weights(oof_dict_pl, y_all)\nprint(f\"Pseudo-labeled ensemble OOF balanced accuracy: {pl_oof_score:.5f} \"\n      f\"(baseline was {own_oof_score:.5f})\")\n\n# Only keep the pseudo-labeled round if it actually beats the honest OOF baseline.\nif pl_oof_score > own_oof_score:\n    own_weights, own_oof_score = pl_weights, pl_oof_score\n    own_blend_oof = sum(w * oof_dict_pl[name] for name, w in own_weights.items())\n    own_blend_test = sum(w * test_dict_pl[name] for name, w in own_weights.items())\n    print(\"-> Using the pseudo-labeled ensemble.\")\nelse:\n    print(\"-> Pseudo-labeling did not help on OOF; keeping the original ensemble.\")","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.9 Blending with public notebook predictions\n\nThe dataset also contains other Kagglers' public submissions (already visible in the file browser: `kosprintr_preds`, `yekenot_preds`, `kirill0212_preds`, `hmnshudhmn24_preds` — each named with its public-LB score). Two improvements over the original fixed `0.6/0.4` blend:\n\n1. **Rank-averaging** instead of raw probability averaging — more robust when different notebooks' probabilities aren't calibrated the same way.\n2. **Score-weighted, not eyeballed** — each notebook's contribution is weighted by how far its known public-LB score is from the best one, via a softmax, rather than a manually picked coefficient.\n\nBecause these files carry no local ground truth (they're test-set-only predictions), the weighting here can't be OOF-validated the way §3.7 was — treat `alpha` below as a knob to tune against your *actual* leaderboard feedback, starting conservative (trusting your own OOF-validated ensemble) and only leaning further on the public blend if it demonstrably helps.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"cols = list(class_order_enc)  # keep column order consistent with our own model outputs\n\npreds_dir = \"/kaggle/input/datasets/vad13irt/ps-s7e6-02072026\"\npublic_files = {\n    \"kosprintr\":     (\"kosprintr_preds_0.95052.csv\", 0.95052),\n    \"yekenot_pl\":    (\"yekenot_preds_pl_0.95040.csv\", 0.95040),\n    \"yekenot\":       (\"yekenot_preds_ 0.95029.csv\", 0.95029),\n    \"kirill0212\":    (\"kirill0212_preds_0.95024.csv\", 0.95024),\n    \"hmnshudhmn24\":  (\"hmnshudhmn24_preds_0.95021.csv\", 0.95021),\n}\n\npublic_probs = {\n    name: pd.read_csv(os.path.join(preds_dir, fname))[cols].values\n    for name, (fname, _) in public_files.items()\n}\n\n\ndef rank_average(prob_matrix):\n    ranks = np.zeros_like(prob_matrix, dtype=float)\n    for j in range(prob_matrix.shape[1]):\n        ranks[:, j] = pd.Series(prob_matrix[:, j]).rank(pct=True).values\n    return ranks\n\n\nscores = np.array([s for _, s in public_files.values()])\npublic_weights = np.exp((scores - scores.min()) * 400)   # sharpen toward the strongest public subs\npublic_weights /= public_weights.sum()\n\npublic_blend = sum(\n    w * rank_average(public_probs[name]) for w, name in zip(public_weights, public_files)\n)\n\nprint(\"Public-notebook blend weights:\")\nfor name, w in zip(public_files, public_weights):\n    print(f\"  {name}: {w:.3f}\")\n\n# alpha: trust in our own OOF-validated ensemble vs. the (locally unvalidated) public blend.\n# Tune against the real leaderboard — raise it if the public blend helps, lower it if not.\nalpha = 0.7\n\nfinal_test_probs = alpha * own_blend_test + (1 - alpha) * public_blend\npreds = class_order_enc[np.argmax(final_test_probs, axis=1)]","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## §3.10 Submission","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"sample_submission","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"test_ids = test[\"id\"].values\n\nsubmission = pd.DataFrame({\n    \"id\": test_ids,\n    \"health_condition\": preds,\n})\n\nsubmission_path = \"submission.csv\"\nsubmission.to_csv(submission_path, index=False)\n\nsubmission","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"figure = plt.figure()\nax = figure.add_subplot()\nplot_count(\n    data_frame=submission,\n    col=\"health_condition\",\n    palette=health_condition_palette,\n    ax=ax,\n)\nfigure.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null}]}